            <fr:title text="difficulties over a noncommutative ring">difficulties over a noncommutative ring</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>The determinant is only really well-defined for matrices in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Mat}_{n}(R)]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is a commutative <fr:link href="/ring-0001/" title="Ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ring-0001/" display-uri="ring-0001" type="local">ring</fr:link>. This is because the determinant "behaves as we expect" for matrices over commutative rings.</html:p>
            <html:p>There are ways to generalize to noncommutative rings, but it depends on how "nice" the ring is.</html:p>
            <html:p>For example, over the quaternions, we can define <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {SL}_{n}(\mathbb {H})]]></fr:tex> since we can embed <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Mat}_{n}(\mathbb {H})]]></fr:tex> as a real subalgebra of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Mat}_{2n}(\mathbb {C})]]></fr:tex>. Then the unit group of this subalgebra is defined to be the general linear group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {GL}_{n}(\mathbb {H})]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>But for, say, the Octonions, we run into difficulties. See Petyt's "<fr:link href="/petyt-2018-special/" title="The special linear group for nonassociative rings" uri="http://localhost:8000/petyt-2018-special/" display-uri="petyt-2018-special" type="local">The special linear group for nonassociative rings</fr:link>".</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
